    <fig id="F3" position="float">
      <label>Figure 3</label>
      <caption>
        <p>A domain in the NH<sub>2</sub>-terminus of mBub1 binds hBub3. (<italic>A</italic>) BHK cells were cotransfected with GFPâhBub3 and Myc-tagged mBub1 expression constructs. After fixation, cells were stained with the 9E10 monoclonal antibody (<italic>red</italic>) to localize mBub1 and Hoechst dye to visualize the chromatin (<italic>blue</italic>). GFP fluorescence is shown in <italic>green</italic>. Coexpression of both full-length mBub1 (<italic>top row</italic>) and the NH<sub>2</sub>-terminal domain (NH<sub>2</sub>-mBub1[400], <italic>middle row</italic>) results in a cytoplasmic sequestration of GFPâhBub3. In contrast, NH<sub>2</sub>-mBub1(400Î38) does not sequester GFPâhBub3 in the cytoplasm (<italic>bottom row</italic>). (<italic>B</italic>) BHK cells were cotransfected with 0.5 Î¼g of GFPâhBub3 and increasing amounts of full-length mBub1 (<italic>solid squares</italic>), the NH<sub>2</sub>-terminal domain (amino acids 1â331) (<italic>solid circles</italic>), the central domain (amino acids 332â731) (<italic>open triangles</italic>), the COOH-terminal kinase domain (amino acids 732â1,058) (<italic>open circles</italic>) or a control plasmid (<italic>open diamonds</italic>). The total amount of DNA used in each transfection was maintained at 2.0 Î¼g by addition of carrier DNA where necessary. The percentage of cells with cytoplasmic GFPâhBub3 was scored and plotted against the amount of cotransfected mBub1. Only coexpression of full-length mBub1 and the NH<sub>2</sub>-terminal domain resulted in a dose-dependent, cytoplasmic sequestration of GFPâhBub3. (<italic>C</italic>) BHK cells were transfected with GSTâhBub3 (lanes <italic>1</italic>, <italic>4</italic>, and <italic>5</italic>) and/or Myc-tagged NH<sub>2</sub>-mBub1(400) (lanes <italic>2</italic> and <italic>4</italic>) and/or Myc-tagged NH<sub>2</sub>-mBub1(400Î38) (lanes <italic>3</italic> and <italic>5</italic>). Proteins from cell lysates (<italic>top</italic>) and purified GSTâhBub3 complexes (<italic>bottom</italic>) were resolved by SDS-PAGE, transferred to a membrane, and then probed with anti-GST and anti-Myc antibodies. In the absence of GSTâhBub3, neither NH<sub>2</sub>-mBub1(400) nor NH<sub>2</sub>-mBub1(400Î38) purify with the glutathione beads (lanes <italic>2</italic> and <italic>3</italic>). In the presence of GSTâhBub3, NH<sub>2</sub>-mBub1(400) does purify with the glutathione beads (lane <italic>4</italic>) but NH<sub>2</sub>-mBub1(400Î38) does not (lane <italic>5</italic>). Note that GSTâhBub3 cannot be identified in the cell lysates due to several comigrating background bands.</p>
